# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cell-culture-methods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] A **bioreactor** is any manufactured device or system that supports a biologically active environment.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] In one case, a bioreactor is a vessel in which a chemical process is carried out which involves organisms or biochemically active substances derived from such organisms.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] This process can either be aerobic or anaerobic.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] These bioreactors are commonly cylindrical, ranging in size from litres to cubic metres, and are often made of stainless steel.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] It may also refer to a device or system designed to grow cells or tissues in the context of cell culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] These devices are being developed for use in tissue engineering or biochemical/bioprocess engineering.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] On the basis of mode of operation, a bioreactor may be classified as batch, fed batch or continuous (e.g. a continuous stirred-tank reactor model).
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] An example of a continuous bioreactor is the chemostat.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Organisms or biochemically active substances growing in bioreactors may be submerged in liquid medium or may be anchored to the surface of a solid medium.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Submerged cultures may be suspended or immobilized.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Suspension bioreactors may support a wider variety of organisms, since special attachment surfaces are not needed, and can operate at a much larger scale than immobilized cultures.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] However, in a continuously operated process the organisms will be removed from the reactor with the effluent.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Immobilization is a general term describing a wide variety of methods for cell or particle attachment or entrapment.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] It can be applied to basically all types of biocatalysis including enzymes, cellular organelles, animal and plant cells and organs.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Immobilization is useful for continuously operated processes, since the organisms will not be removed with the reactor effluent, but is limited in scale because the microbes are only present on the surfaces of the vessel.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Bioreactor design is a relatively complex engineering task, which is studied in the discipline of biochemical/bioprocess engineering.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Under optimum conditions, the microorganisms or cells are able to perform their desired function with limited production of impurities.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] The environmental conditions inside the bioreactor, such as temperature, nutrient concentrations, pH, and dissolved gases (especially oxygen for aerobic fermentations) affect the growth and productivity of the organisms.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] The temperature of the fermentation medium is maintained by a cooling jacket, coils, or both.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Particularly exothermic fermentations may require the use of external heat exchangers.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Nutrients may be continuously added to the fermenter, as in a fed-batch system, or may be charged into the reactor at the beginning of fermentation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] The pH of the medium is measured and adjusted with small amounts of acid or base, depending upon the fermentation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] For aerobic (and some anaerobic) fermentations, reactant gases (especially oxygen) must be added to the fermentation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Since oxygen is relatively insoluble in water (the basis of nearly all fermentation media), air (or purified oxygen) must be added continuously.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] The action of the rising bubbles helps mix the fermentation medium and also "strips" out waste gases, such as carbon dioxide.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] In practice, bioreactors are often pressurized; this increases the solubility of oxygen in water.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] In an aerobic process, optimal oxygen transfer is sometimes the rate limiting step.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Oxygen is poorly soluble in water—even less in warm fermentation broths—and is relatively scarce in air (20.95%).
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Oxygen transfer is usually helped by agitation, which is also needed to mix nutrients and to keep the fermentation homogeneous.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Gas dispersing agitators are used to break up air bubbles and circulate them throughout the vessel.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Scale-down bioreactors play an important rule in process development as they allow for parameters to be fine-tuned without substantial materials or consumables investments.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] A photobioreactor (PBR) is a bioreactor which incorporates some type of light source (that may be natural sunlight or artificial illumination).
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Virtually any translucent container could be called a PBR, however the term is more commonly used to define a closed system, as opposed to an open storage tank or pond.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Photobioreactors are used to grow small phototrophic organisms such as cyanobacteria, algae, or moss plants.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] These organisms use light through photosynthesis as their energy source and do not require sugars or lipids as energy source.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Consequently, risk of contamination with other organisms like bacteria or fungi is lower in photobioreactors when compared to bioreactors for heterotroph organisms.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Conventional sewage treatment utilises bioreactors to undertake the main purification processes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] In some of these systems, a chemically inert medium with very high surface area is provided as a substrate for the growth of biological film.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Separation of excess biological film takes place in settling tanks or cyclones.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] In other systems aerators supply oxygen to the sewage and biota to create activated sludge in which the biological component is freely mixed in the liquor in "flocs".
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] In these processes, the liquid's biochemical oxygen demand (BOD) is reduced sufficiently to render the contaminated water fit for reuse.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] The biosolids can be collected for further processing, or dried and used as fertilizer.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] An extremely simple version of a sewage bioreactor is a septic tank whereby the sewage is left in situ, with or without additional media to house bacteria.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] In this instance, the biosludge itself is the primary host for the bacteria.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Many cells and tissues, especially mammalian ones, must have a surface or other structural support in order to grow, and agitated environments are often destructive to these cell types and tissues.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Higher organisms, being auxotrophic, also require highly specialized growth media.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] This poses a challenge when the goal is to culture larger quantities of cells for therapeutic production purposes, and a significantly different design is needed compared to industrial bioreactors used for growing protein expression systems such as yeast and bacteria.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Many research groups have developed novel bioreactors for growing specialized tissues and cells on a structural scaffold, in attempt to recreate organ-like tissue structures *in-vitro*.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Among these include tissue bioreactors that can grow heart tissue, skeletal muscle tissue, ligaments, cancer tissue models, and others.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Currently, scaling production of these specialized bioreactors for industrial use remains challenging and is an active area of research.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] For more information on artificial tissue culture, see tissue engineering.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Mini‑bioreactors are small‑scale bioreactor systems with working volumes typically below 0.5 L.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] They are designed to reduce operational costs while enabling extensive parallelization and customization.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Advances such as low‑cost sensors, microcontroller‑based control platforms (e.g., Arduino or Raspberry Pi), and integrated automation allow precise monitoring of parameters including optical density and dissolved oxygen, making them a practical alternative to larger benchtop systems.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] In Adaptive laboratory evolution (ALE), mini‑bioreactors support long‑term cultivation under controlled selective pressures.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] They can operate in batch, chemostat, turbidostat or morbidostat modes, each enabling different strategies for maintaining steady growth conditions or dynamically adjusting stress levels.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Their automation‑ready design facilitates stable operation over many generations, making them valuable tools for studying microbial evolution, metabolic engineering and the development of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Mathematical models act as an important tool in various bio-reactor applications including wastewater treatment.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] These models are useful for planning efficient process control strategies and predicting the future plant performance.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Moreover, these models are beneficial in education and research areas.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Bioreactors are generally used in those industries which are concerned with food, beverages and pharmaceuticals.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] The emergence of *biochemical engineering* is of recent origin.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Processing of biological materials using biological agents such as cells, enzymes or antibodies are the major pillars of biochemical engineering.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Applications of biochemical engineering cover major fields of civilization such as agriculture, food and healthcare, resource recovery and fine chemicals.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Until now, the industries associated with biotechnology have lagged behind other industries in implementing control over the process and optimization strategies.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] A main drawback in biotechnological process control is the problem of measuring key physical and biochemical parameters.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] A bioprocess is composed mainly of three stages—upstream processing, bioreaction, and downstream processing—to convert raw material to finished product.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] The raw material can be of biological or non-biological origin.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] It is first converted to a more suitable form for processing.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] This is done in an upstream processing step which involves chemical hydrolysis, preparation of liquid medium, separation of particulate, air purification and many other preparatory operations.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] After the upstream processing step, the resulting feed is transferred to one or more bioreaction stages.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] The biochemical reactors or bioreactors form the base of the bioreaction step.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] This step mainly consists of three operations, namely, production of biomass, metabolite biosynthesis and biotransformation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] Finally, the material produced in the bioreactor must be further processed in the downstream section to convert it into a more useful form.
[src:cell-culture-methods/bioreactor] The downstream process mainly consists of physical separation operations which include solid liquid separation, adsorption, liquid-liquid extraction, distillation, drying etc.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In practice, the term "cell culture" now refers to the culturing of cells derived from multicellular eukaryotes, especially animal cells, in contrast with other types of culture that also grow cells, such as plant tissue culture, fungal culture, and microbiological culture (of microbes).
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The historical development and methods of cell culture are closely interrelated with those of tissue culture and organ culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Viral culture is also related, with cells as hosts for the viruses.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The laboratory technique of maintaining live cell lines (a population of cells descended from a single cell and containing the same genetic makeup) separated from their original tissue source became more robust in the middle 20th century.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The 19th-century English physiologist Sydney Ringer developed salt solutions containing the chlorides of sodium, potassium, calcium and magnesium suitable for maintaining the beating of an isolated animal heart outside the body.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In 1885 Wilhelm Roux removed a section of the medullary plate of an embryonic chicken and maintained it in a warm saline solution for several days, establishing the basic principle of tissue culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In 1907 the zoologist Ross Granville Harrison demonstrated the growth of frog embryonic cells that would give rise to nerve cells in a medium of clotted lymph.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Lambert grew vaccinia virus in fragments of guinea pig corneal tissue.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In 1996, the first use of regenerative tissue was used to replace a small length of urethra, which led to the understanding that the technique of obtaining samples of tissue, growing it outside the body without a scaffold, and reapplying it, can be used for only small distances of less than 1 cm.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Ross Granville Harrison, working at Johns Hopkins Medical School and then at Yale University, published results of his experiments from 1907 to 1910, establishing the methodology of tissue culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Gottlieb Haberlandt first pointed out the possibilities of the culture of isolated tissues, plant tissue culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] He suggested that the potentialities of individual cells via tissue culture as well as that the reciprocal influences of tissues on one another could be determined by this method.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Since Haberlandt's original assertions, methods for tissue and cell culture have been realized, leading to significant discoveries in biology and medicine.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] He presented his original idea of *totipotentiality* in 1902, stating that "Theoretically all plant cells are able to give rise to a complete plant." The term *tissue culture* was coined by American pathologist Montrose Thomas Burrows.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cell culture techniques were advanced significantly in the 1940s and 1950s to support research in virology.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Growing viruses in cell cultures allowed preparation of purified viruses for the manufacture of vaccines.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The injectable polio vaccine developed by Jonas Salk was one of the first products mass-produced using cell culture techniques.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] This vaccine was made possible by the cell culture research of John Franklin Enders, Thomas Huckle Weller, and Frederick Chapman Robbins, who were awarded a Nobel Prize for their discovery of a method of growing the virus in monkey kidney cell cultures.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cell culture has contributed to the development of vaccines for many diseases.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In modern usage, "tissue culture" generally refers to the growth of cells from a tissue from a multicellular organism *in vitro*.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] These cells may be cells isolated from a donor organism (primary cells) or an immortalised cell line.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The cells are bathed in a culture medium, which contains essential nutrients and energy sources necessary for the cells' survival.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Thus, in its broader sense, "tissue culture" is often used interchangeably with "cell culture".
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] On the other hand, the strict meaning of "tissue culture" refers to the culturing of tissue pieces, i.e. explant culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Tissue culture is an important tool for the study of the biology of cells from multicellular organisms.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] It provides an *in vitro* model of the tissue in a well defined environment which can be easily manipulated and analysed.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In animal tissue culture, cells may be grown as two-dimensional monolayers (conventional culture) or within fibrous scaffolds or gels to attain more naturalistic three-dimensional tissue-like structures (3D culture).
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] A 1988 NIH SBIR grant report showed that electrospinning could be used to produce nano- and submicron-scale polymeric fibrous scaffolds specifically intended for use as *in vitro* cell and tissue substrates.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] This early use of electrospun fibrous lattices for cell culture and tissue engineering showed that various cell types would adhere to and proliferate upon polycarbonate fibers.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] It was noted that as opposed to the flattened morphology typically seen in 2D culture, cells grown on the electrospun fibers exhibited a more rounded 3-dimensional morphology generally observed of tissues *in vivo*.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Plant tissue culture in particular is concerned with the growing of entire plants from small pieces of plant tissue, cultured in medium.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cells can be isolated from tissues for *ex vivo* culture in several ways.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cells can be easily purified from blood; however, only the white cells are capable of growth in culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cells can be isolated from solid tissues by digesting the extracellular matrix using enzymes such as collagenase, trypsin, or pronase, before agitating the tissue to release the cells into suspension.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Alternatively, pieces of tissue can be placed in growth media, and the cells that grow out are available for culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] This method is known as explant culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cells that are cultured directly from a subject are known as primary cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] With the exception of some derived from tumors, most primary cell cultures have limited lifespan.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] An established or immortalized cell line has acquired the ability to proliferate indefinitely either through random mutation or deliberate modification, such as artificial expression of the telomerase gene.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Numerous cell lines are well established as representative of particular cell types.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] For the majority of isolated primary cells, they undergo the process of senescence and stop dividing after a certain number of population doublings while generally retaining their viability (described as the Hayflick limit).
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Aside from temperature and gas mixture, the most commonly varied factor in culture systems is the cell growth medium.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Recipes for growth media can vary in pH, glucose concentration, growth factors, and the presence of other nutrients.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The growth factors used to supplement media are often derived from the serum of animal blood, such as fetal bovine serum (FBS), bovine calf serum, equine serum, and porcine serum.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] One complication of these blood-derived ingredients is the potential for contamination of the culture with viruses or prions, particularly in medical biotechnology applications.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Current practice is to minimize or eliminate the use of these ingredients wherever possible and use human platelet lysate (hPL).
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] This eliminates the worry of cross-species contamination when using FBS with human cells. hPL has emerged as a safe and reliable alternative as a direct replacement for FBS or other animal serum.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In addition, chemically defined media can be used to eliminate any serum trace (human or animal), but this cannot always be accomplished with different cell types.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Alternative strategies involve sourcing the animal blood from countries with minimum BSE/TSE risk, such as The United States, Australia and New Zealand, and using purified nutrient concentrates derived from serum in place of whole animal serum for cell culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Plating density (number of cells per volume of culture medium) plays a critical role for some cell types.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] For example, a lower plating density makes granulosa cells exhibit estrogen production, while a higher plating density makes them appear as progesterone-producing theca lutein cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cells can be grown either in suspension or **adherent cultures**.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Some cells naturally live in suspension, without being attached to a surface, such as cells that exist in the bloodstream.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] There are also cell lines that have been modified to be able to survive in suspension cultures so they can be grown to a higher density than adherent conditions would allow.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Adherent cells require a surface, such as tissue culture plastic or microcarrier, which may be coated with extracellular matrix (such as collagen and laminin) components to increase adhesion properties and provide other signals needed for growth and differentiation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Most cells derived from solid tissues are adherent.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Another type of adherent culture is **organotypic culture**, which involves growing cells in a three-dimensional (3-D) environment as opposed to two-dimensional culture dishes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] This 3D culture system is biochemically and physiologically more similar to *in vivo* tissue, but is technically challenging to maintain because of many factors (e.g. diffusion).
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cell line cross-contamination can be a problem for scientists working with cultured cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Studies suggest anywhere from 15 to 20% of the time, cells used in experiments have been misidentified or contaminated with another cell line.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Problems with cell line cross-contamination have even been detected in lines from the NCI-60 panel, which are used routinely for drug-screening studies.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Major cell line repositories, including the American Type Culture Collection (ATCC), the European Collection of Cell Cultures (ECACC) and the German Collection of Microorganisms and Cell Cultures (DSMZ), have received cell line submissions from researchers that were misidentified by them.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Such contamination poses a problem for the quality of research produced using cell culture lines, and the major repositories are now authenticating all cell line submissions.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] ATCC uses short tandem repeat (STR) DNA fingerprinting to authenticate its cell lines.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] To address this problem of cell line cross-contamination, researchers are encouraged to authenticate their cell lines at an early passage to establish the identity of the cell line.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Authentication should be repeated before freezing cell line stocks, every two months during active culturing and before any publication of research data generated using the cell lines.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Many methods are used to identify cell lines, including isoenzyme analysis, human lymphocyte antigen (HLA) typing, chromosomal analysis, karyotyping, morphology and STR analysis.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] One significant cell-line cross contaminant is the immortal HeLa cell line.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] HeLa contamination was first noted in the early 1960s in non-human culture in the USA.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Intraspecies contamination was discovered in nineteen cell lines in the seventies.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In 1974, five human cell lines from the Soviet Union were found to be HeLa.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] A follow-up study analysing 50-odd cell lines indicated that half had HeLa markers, but contaminant HeLa had hybridised with the original cell lines.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] HeLa cell contamination from air droplets has been reported.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] HeLa was even unknowingly injected into human subjects by Jonas Salk in a 1978 vaccine trial.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] As cells generally continue to divide in culture, they generally grow to fill the available area or volume.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The choice of culture medium might affect the physiological relevance of findings from cell culture experiments due to the differences in the nutrient composition and concentrations.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] A systematic bias in generated datasets was recently shown for CRISPR and RNAi gene silencing screens, and for metabolic profiling of cancer cell lines.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Using a growth medium that better represents the physiological levels of nutrients can improve the physiological relevance of in vitro studies and recently such media types, as Plasmax and Human Plasma Like Medium (HPLM), were developed.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Among the common manipulations carried out on culture cells are media changes, passaging cells, and transfecting cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] These are generally performed using tissue culture methods that rely on aseptic technique.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Aseptic technique aims to avoid contamination with bacteria, yeast, or other cell lines.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Manipulations are typically carried out in a biosafety cabinet or laminar flow cabinet to exclude contaminating micro-organisms.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Antibiotics (e.g. penicillin and streptomycin) and antifungals (e.g.amphotericin B and Antibiotic-Antimycotic solution) can also be added to the growth media.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] As cells undergo metabolic processes, acid is produced and the pH decreases.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Often, a pH indicator is added to the medium to measure nutrient depletion.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In the case of adherent cultures, the media can be removed directly by aspiration, and then is replaced.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Media changes in non-adherent cultures involve centrifuging the culture and resuspending the cells in fresh media.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Passaging (also known as subculture or splitting cells) involves transferring a small number of cells into a new vessel.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cells can be cultured for a longer time if they are split regularly, as it avoids the senescence associated with prolonged high cell density.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Suspension cultures are easily passaged with a small amount of culture containing a few cells diluted in a larger volume of fresh media.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] For adherent cultures, cells first need to be detached; this is commonly done with a mixture of trypsin-EDTA; however, other enzyme mixes are now available for this purpose.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] A small number of detached cells can then be used to seed a new culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Some cell cultures, such as RAW cells are mechanically scraped from the surface of their vessel with rubber scrapers.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Another common method for manipulating cells involves the introduction of foreign DNA by transfection.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] This is often performed to cause cells to express a gene of interest.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] More recently, the transfection of RNAi constructs have been realized as a convenient mechanism for suppressing the expression of a particular gene/protein.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] DNA can also be inserted into cells using viruses, in methods referred to as transduction, infection or transformation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Viruses, as parasitic agents, are well suited to introducing DNA into cells, as this is a part of their normal course of reproduction.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cell lines that originate with humans have been somewhat controversial in bioethics, as they may outlive their parent organism and later be used in the discovery of lucrative medical treatments.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In the pioneering decision in this area, the Supreme Court of California held in *Moore v.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Regents of the University of California* that human patients have no property rights in cell lines derived from organs removed with their consent.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] It is possible to fuse normal cells with an immortalised cell line.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] This method is used to produce monoclonal antibodies.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In brief, lymphocytes isolated from the spleen (or possibly blood) of an immunised animal are combined with an immortal myeloma cell line (B cell lineage) to produce a hybridoma which has the antibody specificity of the primary lymphocyte and the immortality of the myeloma.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Selective growth medium (HA or HAT) is used to select against unfused myeloma cells; primary lymphoctyes die quickly in culture and only the fused cells survive.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] These are screened for production of the required antibody, generally in pools to start with and then after single cloning.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] A cell strain is derived either from a primary culture or a cell line by the selection or cloning of cells having specific properties or characteristics which must be defined.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cell strains are cells that have been adapted to culture but, unlike cell lines, have a finite division potential.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Non-immortalized cells stop dividing after 40 to 60 population doublings and, after this, they lose their ability to proliferate (a genetically determined event known as senescence).
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Mass culture of animal cell lines is fundamental to the manufacture of viral vaccines and other products of biotechnology.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Culture of human stem cells is used to expand the number of cells and differentiate the cells into various somatic cell types for transplantation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Stem cell culture is also used to harvest the molecules and exosomes that the stem cells release for the purposes of therapeutic development.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Biological products produced by recombinant DNA (rDNA) technology in animal cell cultures include enzymes, synthetic hormones, immunobiologicals (monoclonal antibodies, interleukins, lymphokines), and anticancer agents.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Although many simpler proteins can be produced using rDNA in bacterial cultures, more complex proteins that are glycosylated (carbohydrate-modified) currently must be made in animal cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Mammalian cells ensure expressed proteins are folded correctly and possess human-like glycosylation and post-translational modifications.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] An important example of such a complex protein is the hormone erythropoietin.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] It also offers to confirm single cell origin of somatic embryos and the asymmetry of the first cell division, which starts the process.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cell culture is also a key technique for cellular agriculture, which aims to provide both new products and new ways of producing existing agricultural products like milk, (cultured) meat, fragrances, and rhino horn from cells and microorganisms.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] It is therefore considered one means of achieving animal-free agriculture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] It is also a central tool for teaching cell biology.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Research in tissue engineering, stem cells and molecular biology primarily involves cultures of cells on flat plastic dishes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] This technique is known as two-dimensional (2D) cell culture, and was first developed by Wilhelm Roux who, in 1885, removed a portion of the medullary plate of an embryonic chicken and maintained it in warm saline for several days on a flat glass plate.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] From the advance of polymer technology arose today's standard plastic dish for 2D cell culture, commonly known as the Petri dish.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Julius Richard Petri, a German bacteriologist, is generally credited with this invention while working as an assistant to Robert Koch.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Various researchers today also utilize culturing laboratory flasks, conicals, and even disposable bags like those used in single-use bioreactors.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Aside from Petri dishes, scientists have long been growing cells within biologically derived matrices such as collagen or fibrin, and more recently, on synthetic hydrogels such as polyacrylamide or PEG.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] They do this in order to elicit phenotypes that are not expressed on conventionally rigid substrates.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cell culture in three dimensions has been touted as "Biology's New Dimension".
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] At present, the practice of cell culture remains based on varying combinations of single or multiple cell structures in 2D.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Currently, there is an increase in use of 3D cell cultures in research areas including drug discovery, cancer biology, regenerative medicine, nanomaterials assessment and basic life science research.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] 3D cell cultures can be grown using a scaffold or matrix, or in a scaffold-free manner.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Scaffold based cultures utilize an acellular 3D matrix or a liquid matrix.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Scaffold-free methods are normally generated in suspensions.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Culturing cells in 3D leads to wide variation in gene expression signatures and partly mimics tissues in the physiological states.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] A 3D cell culture model showed cell growth similar to that of in vivo than did a monolayer culture, and all three cultures were capable of sustaining cell growth.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] As 3D culturing has been developed it turns out to have a great potential to design tumors models and investigate malignant transformation and metastasis, 3D cultures can provide aggerate tool for understanding changes, interactions, and cellular signaling.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Eric Simon, in a 1988 NIH SBIR grant report, showed that electrospinning could be used to produce nano- and submicron-scale polystyrene and polycarbonate fibrous scaffolds specifically intended for use as *in vitro* cell substrates.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] This early use of electrospun fibrous lattices for cell culture and tissue engineering showed that various cell types including Human Foreskin Fibroblasts (HFF), transformed Human Carcinoma (HEp-2), and Mink Lung Epithelium (MLE) would adhere to and proliferate upon polycarbonate fibers.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] It was noted that, as opposed to the flattened morphology typically seen in 2D culture, cells grown on the electrospun fibers exhibited a more histotypic rounded 3-dimensional morphology generally observed *in vivo*.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] As the natural extracellular matrix (ECM) is important in the survival, proliferation, differentiation and migration of cells, different hydrogel culture matrices mimicking natural ECM structure are seen as potential approaches to in vivo–like cell culturing.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Hydrogels are composed of interconnected pores with high water retention, which enables efficient transport of substances such as nutrients and gases.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Several different types of hydrogels from natural and synthetic materials are available for 3D cell culture, including animal ECM extract hydrogels, protein hydrogels, peptide hydrogels, polymer hydrogels, and wood-based nanocellulose hydrogel.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The magnetic nanoparticle assemblies consist of magnetic iron oxide nanoparticles, gold nanoparticles, and the polymer polylysine.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] 3D cell culturing is scalable, with the capability for culturing 500 cells to millions of cells or from single dish to high-throughput low volume systems.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cell culture is a fundamental component of tissue culture and tissue engineering, as it establishes the basics of growing and maintaining cells *in vitro*.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The major application of human cell culture is in stem cell industry, where mesenchymal stem cells are isolated, cultured, and subjected to long-term storage via optimized cryopreservation, so as to retain stable differentiation and immunomodulatory properties post-thaw for future applications.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Tissue engineering potentially offers dramatic improvements in low cost medical care for hundreds of thousands of patients annually.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Vaccines for polio, measles, mumps, rubella, and chickenpox are currently made in cell cultures.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Due to the H5N1 pandemic threat, research into using cell culture for influenza vaccines is being funded by the United States government.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Novel ideas in the field include recombinant DNA-based vaccines, such as one made using human adenovirus (a common cold virus) as a vector, and novel adjuvants.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The technique of co-culturing is used to study cell crosstalk between two or more types of cells on a plate or in a 3D matrix.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The cultivation of different stem cells and the interaction of immune cells can be investigated in an in vitro model similar to biological tissue.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Since most tissues contain more than one type of cell, it is important to evaluate their interaction in a 3D culture environment to gain a better understanding of their interaction and to introduce mimetic tissues.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] There are two types of co-culturing: direct and indirect.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] While direct interaction involves cells being in direct contact with each other in the same culture media or matrix, indirect interaction involves different environments, allowing signaling and soluble factors to participate.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cell differentiation in tissue models during interaction between cells can be studied using the Co-Cultured System to simulate cancer tumors, to assess the effect of drugs on therapeutic trials, and to study the effect of drugs on therapeutic trials.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The co-culture system in 3D models can predict the response to chemotherapy and endocrine therapy if the microenvironment defines biological tissue for the cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] A co-culture method is used in tissue engineering to generate tissue formation with multiple cells interacting directly.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Microfluidics technique is developed systems that can perform a process in a flow which are usually in a scale of micron.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Microfluidics chip are also known as Lab-on-a-chip and they are able to have continuous procedure and reaction steps with spare amount of reactants and space.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Such systems enable the identification and isolation of individual cells and molecules when combined with appropriate biological assays and high-sensitivity detection techniques.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] OoC systems mimic and control the microenvironment of the cells by growing tissues in microfluidics.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Combining tissue engineering, biomaterials fabrication, and cell biology, it offers the possibility of establishing a biomimetic model for studying human diseases in the laboratory.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] In recent years, 3D cell culture science has made significant progress, leading to the development of OoC.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] OoC is considered as a preclinical step that benefits pharmaceutical studies, drug development and disease modeling.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] OoC is an important technology that can bridge the gap between animal testing and clinical studies and also by the advances that the science has achieved could be a replace for in vivo studies for drug delivery and pathophysiological studies.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Besides the culture of well-established immortalised cell lines, cells from primary explants of a plethora of organisms can be cultured for a limited period of time before senescence occurs (see Hayflick's limit).
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cultured primary cells have been extensively used in research, as is the case of fish keratocytes in cell migration studies.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Plant cell cultures are typically grown as cell suspension cultures in a liquid medium or as callus cultures on a solid medium.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The culturing of undifferentiated plant cells and calli requires the proper balance of the plant growth hormones auxin and cytokinin.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cells derived from *Drosophila melanogaster* (most prominently, Schneider 2 cells) can be used for experiments which may be hard to do on live flies or larvae, such as biochemical studies or studies using siRNA.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Cell lines derived from the army worm *Spodoptera frugiperda*, including Sf9 and Sf21, and from the cabbage looper *Trichoplusia ni*, High Five cells, are commonly used for expression of recombinant proteins using baculovirus.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] For bacteria and yeasts, small quantities of cells are usually grown on a solid support that contains nutrients embedded in it, usually a gel such as agar, while large-scale cultures are grown with the cells suspended in a nutrient broth.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] The culture of viruses requires the culture of cells of mammalian, plant, fungal or bacterial origin as hosts for the growth and replication of the virus.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Whole wild type viruses, recombinant viruses or viral products may be generated in cell types other than their natural hosts under the right conditions.
[src:cell-culture-methods/cell-culture] Depending on the species of the virus, infection and viral replication may result in host cell lysis and formation of a viral plaque.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] A **growth medium** or **culture medium** is a solid, liquid, or semi-solid designed to support the growth of a population of microorganisms or cells via the process of cell proliferation or small plants like the moss *Physcomitrella patens*.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Different types of media are used for growing different types of cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] The two major types of growth media are those used for cell culture, which use specific cell types derived from plants or animals, and those used for microbiological culture, which are used for growing microorganisms such as bacteria or fungi.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] The most common growth media for microorganisms are nutrient broths and agar plates; specialized media are sometimes required for microorganism and cell culture growth.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Some organisms, termed fastidious organisms, require specialized environments due to complex nutritional requirements.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Viruses, for example, are obligate intracellular parasites and require a growth medium containing living cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] The most common growth media for microorganisms are nutrient broths (liquid nutrient medium) or lysogeny broth medium.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Liquid media are often mixed with agar and poured via a sterile media dispenser into Petri dishes to solidify.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] These agar plates provide a solid medium on which microbes may be cultured.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] They remain solid, as very few bacteria are able to decompose agar (the exception being some species in the genera: *Cytophaga*, *Flavobacterium*, *Bacillus*, *Pseudomonas*, and *Alcaligenes*).
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Bacteria grown in liquid cultures often form colloidal suspensions.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] The difference between growth media used for cell culture and those used for microbiological culture is that cells derived from whole organisms and grown in culture often cannot grow without the addition of, for instance, hormones or growth factors which usually occur *in vivo*.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] In the case of animal cells, this difficulty is often addressed by the addition of blood serum or a synthetic serum replacement to the medium.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] In the case of microorganisms, no such limitations exist, as they are often unicellular organisms.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] One other major difference is that animal cells in culture are often grown on a flat surface to which they attach, and the medium is provided in a liquid form, which covers the cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] In contrast, bacteria such as *Escherichia coli* may be grown on solid or in liquid media.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] An important distinction between growth media types is that of chemically defined versus undefined media.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] A defined medium will have known quantities of all ingredients.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] For microorganisms, they consist of providing trace elements and vitamins required by the microbe and especially defined carbon and nitrogen sources.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Glucose or glycerol are often used as carbon sources, and ammonium salts or nitrates as inorganic nitrogen sources.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] An undefined medium has some complex ingredients, such as yeast extract or casein hydrolysate, which consist of a mixture of many chemical species in unknown proportions.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Undefined media are sometimes chosen based on price and sometimes by necessity – some microorganisms have never been cultured on defined media.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] A good example of a growth medium is the wort used to make beer.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] The wort contains all the nutrients required for yeast growth, and under anaerobic conditions, alcohol is produced.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] When the fermentation process is complete, the combination of medium and dormant microbes, now beer, is ready for consumption.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Culture media contain all the elements that most bacteria need for growth and are not selective, so they are used for the general cultivation and maintenance of bacteria kept in laboratory culture collections.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] This is an undefined medium because the amino-acid source contains a variety of compounds; the exact composition is unknown.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] A defined medium that has just enough ingredients to support growth is called a "minimal medium".
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] The number of ingredients that must be added to a minimal medium varies enormously depending on which microorganism is being grown.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Minimal media are those that contain the minimum nutrients possible for colony growth, generally without the presence of amino acids, and are often used by microbiologists and geneticists to grow "wild-type" microorganisms.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Minimal media can also be used to select for or against recombinants or exconjugants.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Supplementary minimal media are minimal media that also contains a single selected agent, usually an amino acid or a sugar.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] This supplementation allows for the culturing of specific lines of auxotrophic recombinants.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Selective media are used for the growth of only selected microorganisms.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] For example, if a microorganism is resistant to a certain antibiotic, such as ampicillin or tetracycline, then that antibiotic can be added to the medium to prevent other cells, which do not possess the resistance, from growing.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Media lacking an amino acid such as proline in conjunction with *E. coli* unable to synthesize it were commonly used by geneticists before the emergence of genomics to map bacterial chromosomes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Selective growth media are also used in cell culture to ensure the survival or proliferation of cells with certain properties, such as antibiotic resistance or the ability to synthesize a certain metabolite.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Normally, the presence of a specific gene or an allele of a gene confers upon the cell the ability to grow in the selective medium.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] In such cases, the gene is termed a marker.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Selective growth media for eukaryotic cells commonly contain neomycin to select cells that have been successfully transfected with a plasmid carrying the neomycin resistance gene as a marker.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Gancyclovir is an exception to the rule, as it is used to specifically kill cells that carry its respective marker, the Herpes simplex virus thymidine kinase.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Differential or indicator media distinguish one microorganism type from another growing on the same medium.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] This type of media uses the biochemical characteristics of a microorganism growing in the presence of specific nutrients or indicators (such as neutral red, phenol red, eosin y, or methylene blue) added to the medium to visibly indicate the defining characteristics of a microorganism.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] These media are used for the detection of microorganisms and by molecular biologists to detect recombinant strains of bacteria.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Enriched media contain the nutrients required to support the growth of a wide variety of organisms, including some of the more fastidious ones.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] They are commonly used to harvest as many different types of microbes as are present in the specimen.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Blood agar is an enriched medium in which nutritionally rich whole blood supplements the basic nutrients.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Chocolate agar is enriched with heat-treated blood (40–45 °C or 104–113 °F), which turns brown and gives the medium the color for which it is named.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] The choice of culture medium might affect the physiological relevance of findings from tissue culture experiments, especially for metabolic studies.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] In addition, the dependence of a cell line on a metabolic gene was shown to be affected by the media type.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] When performing a study involving several cell lines, utilizing a uniform culture media for all cell lines might reduce the bias in the generated datasets.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Using a growth medium that better represents the physiological levels of nutrients can improve the physiological relevance of in vitro studies and recently such media types, as Plasmax and human plasma-like medium (HPLM), were developed.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] The selection of cell culture medium is crucial for efficient mammalian cell culture, significantly affecting cell growth, productivity, and consistency across batches.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] In protein expression, the choice of media can also influence the therapeutic characteristics of produced proteins through processes like glycosylation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Different types of media, such as serum-containing, serum-free, protein-free, and chemically defined media, have distinct benefits and drawbacks.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Serum-containing media are rich in growth factors but can lead to variability and contamination issues.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Fetal bovine serum (FBS) is commonly used due to its high capacity to support cell growth, although it poses biosafety concerns due to its inconsistent composition.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] In contrast, serum-free media (SFM) offer standardized formulations that enhance reliability and reduce contamination risks.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] They are designed to include essential nutrients like amino acids, vitamins, and glucose, but can sometimes provide weaker growth performance compared to serum-containing alternatives.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] The development of protein-free and chemically defined media is aimed at achieving greater consistency and control in cell culture processes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/growth-medium] Ultimately, the composition of the culture medium directly impacts cell viability and productivity, making the careful selection and design of culture media essential for successful mammalian cell culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The cells from Lacks's cancerous cervical tumor were taken without her knowledge, which was common practice in the United States at the time.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Cell biologist George Otto Gey found that they could be kept alive, and developed a cell line.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Previously, cells cultured from other human cells would survive for only a few days, but cells from Lacks's tumor behaved differently.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In 1951, Henrietta Lacks was admitted to the Johns Hopkins Hospital with symptoms of irregular vaginal bleeding; she was subsequently treated for cervical cancer.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Her first treatment was performed by Lawrence Wharton Jr., who at that time collected tissue samples from her cervix without her consent.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Her cervical biopsy supplied samples of tissue for clinical evaluation and research by George Otto Gey, head of the Tissue Culture Laboratory.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Gey's lab assistant Mary Kubicek used the roller-tube technique to culture the cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] It was observed that the cells grew robustly, doubling every 20–24 hours, unlike previous specimens, which died out.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The cells were propagated by Gey shortly before Lacks died of her cancer in 1951.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] This was the first human cell line to prove successful in vitro, which was a scientific achievement with profound future benefit to medical research.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Gey freely donated these cells, along with the tools and processes that his lab developed, to any scientist requesting them, simply for the benefit of science.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Neither Lacks nor her family gave permission to harvest the cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The cells were later commercialized, although never patented in their original form.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] There was no requirement at that time to inform patients or their relatives about such matters, because discarded material or material obtained during surgery, diagnosis, or therapy was considered the property of the physician or the medical institution.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] As was customary for Gey's lab assistant, the culture was named after the first two letters of Henrietta Lacks' first and last names, He + La.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Before a 1973 query printed in the journal *Nature* obtained her real name, the "HeLa" cell line was incorrectly attributed to a "Helen Lane" or "Helen Larson".
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The origin of this obfuscation is unclear.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In 1973, staff at Johns Hopkins discovered that HeLa cells could travel through the air and easily contaminate other cell cultures.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] When staff at Johns Hopkins realized this, a staff physician contacted the Lacks family and sought DNA samples to help identify which non-HeLa cultures were contaminated with HeLa cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The family never understood the purpose of the visit, but they were distressed by their understanding of what the researchers told them.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] These cells are treated as cancer cells, as they are descended from a biopsy taken from a visible lesion on the cervix as part of Lacks's diagnosis of cancer.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells, like other cell lines, are termed "immortal" because they can divide an unlimited number of times in a laboratory cell culture plate, as long as fundamental cell survival conditions are met (i.e. being maintained and sustained in a suitable environment).
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] There are many strains of HeLa cells, because they mutate during division in cell cultures, but all HeLa cells are descended from the same tumor cells removed from Lacks.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The total number of HeLa cells that have been propagated in cell culture far exceeds the total number of cells that were in Henrietta Lacks's body.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Lacks's case is one of many examples of the lack of informed consent in 20th-century medicine.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Communication between tissue donors and doctors was virtually nonexistent—cells were taken without patient consent, and patients were not told what the cells would be used for.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Johns Hopkins Hospital, where Lacks received treatment and had her tissue harvested, was the only hospital in the Baltimore area where African American patients could receive free care.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The patients who received free care from this segregated sect of the hospital often became research subjects without their knowledge.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Lacks' family also had no access to her patient files and had no say in who received HeLa cells or what they would be used for.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Additionally, as HeLa cells were popularized and used more frequently throughout the scientific community, Lacks' relatives received no financial benefit and continued to live with limited access to healthcare.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] This issue of who owns tissue samples taken for research was brought up in the Supreme Court of California case of *Moore v.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Regents of the University of California* in 1990.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The court ruled that a person's discarded tissue and cells are not his or her property and can be commercialized.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Lacks's case influenced the establishment of the Common Rule in 1991.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The Common Rule enforces informed consent by ensuring that doctors inform patients if they plan to use any details of the patient's case in research and give them the choice of disclosing the details or not.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Tissues connected to their donors' names are also strictly regulated under this rule, and samples are no longer named using donors' initials, but rather by code numbers.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] To further resolve the issue of patient privacy, Johns Hopkins established a joint committee with the NIH and several of Lacks's family members to determine who receives access to Henrietta Lacks's genome.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In 2021, Henrietta Lacks's estate sued to get past and future payments for the alleged unauthorized and widely known sale of HeLa cells by Thermo Fisher Scientific.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Lacks's family hired an attorney to seek compensation from upwards of 100 pharmaceutical companies that have used and profited from HeLa cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Settlement of the suit with Thermo Fisher Scientific was announced in August 2023, with undisclosed terms.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Novartis, a company that developed hundreds of patents using HeLa cells, settled in 2026.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] As of March 2026, lawsuits against Ultragenyx and Viatris are still pending.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells were the first human cells to be successfully cloned in 1953, by Theodore Puck and Philip I.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Marcus at the University of Colorado, Denver.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The many different sublineages of HeLa cells have each developed their own characteristics and can yield different results in the same experiment.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] As a result researchers should be specific about the lineage and batch used.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells were used by Jonas Salk to test the first polio vaccine in the 1950s.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] They were observed to be easily infected by the poliomyelitis virus, causing infected cells to die.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] This made HeLa cells highly desirable for polio vaccine testing, since results could be easily obtained.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] A large volume of HeLa cells were needed for the testing of Salk's polio vaccine, prompting the National Foundation for Infantile Paralysis (NFIP) to find a facility capable of mass-producing HeLa cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In the spring of 1953, a cell culture factory was established at Tuskegee University to supply Salk and other labs with HeLa cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Less than a year later, Salk's vaccine was ready for human trials.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells have been used in testing how parvovirus infects cells of humans, dogs, and cats.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] These cells have also been used to study viruses such as the oropouche virus (OROV).
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] OROV causes disruption of cells in culture; the cells start to degenerate shortly after they are infected, causing viral induction of apoptosis.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells have been used to study expression of the papillomavirus E2 and apoptosis.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells have also been used to study the ability of the canine distemper virus to induce apoptosis in cancer cell lines, which could play an important role in developing treatments for tumor cells resistant to radiation and chemotherapy.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Over the years, HeLa cells have been infected with various types of viruses, including HIV, Zika, mumps, and herpes viruses to test and develop new vaccines and drugs.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Richard Axel discovered that the addition of the CD4 protein to HeLa cells enabled them to be infected with HIV, allowing the virus to be studied.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In 1979, scientists learned that the measles virus constantly mutates when it infects HeLa cells, and in 2019 they found that Zika cannot multiply in HeLa cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells have also been instrumental in the recognition of human papillomavirus infection as a precursor to cervical cancer.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In the 1980s, Harald zur Hausen found that Lacks's cells from the original biopsy contained HPV-18, which was later found to be the cause of the aggressive cancer that had killed her.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] His work in linking HPV with cervical cancer won him a Nobel Prize.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] This discovery lead to the use of HPV tests to identify those at high risk of developing cervical cancer and the development of HPV vaccines to prevent the cancer-causing infection.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Populations that have received the vaccine consistently show much lower rates of cervical cancer with a reduction of 90% among those who received the vaccine before 17 years of age.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In low- and middle-income countries, 11.24 deaths are prevented per 1,000 HPV-vaccinated people, the highest for all analyzed vaccines..
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells have been used in a number of cancer studies, including those involving sex steroid hormones, such as estradiol and other estrogens, and estrogen receptors, along with estrogen-like compounds, such as quercetin, which has cancer-reducing properties.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] There have also been studies on HeLa cells, involving the effects of flavonoids and antioxidants with estradiol on cancer cell proliferation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In 2011, HeLa cells were used in tests of novel heptamethine dyes IR-808 and other analogues, which are currently being explored for their unique uses in medical diagnostics, the individualized treatment of cancer patients with the aid of PDT, co-administration with other drugs, and irradiation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells have been used in research involving fullerenes to induce apoptosis as a part of photodynamic therapy, as well as in *in vitro* cancer research using cell lines.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells have also been used to define cancer markers in RNA, and have been used to establish an RNAi Based Identification System and Interference of Specific Cancer Cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In 2014, HeLa cells were shown to provide a viable cell line for tumor xenografts in C57BL/6 nude mice, and were subsequently used to examine the *in vivo* effects of fluoxetine and cisplatin on cervical cancer.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In 1965, Henry Harris and John Watkins created the first human-animal hybrid by fusing HeLa cells with mouse embryo cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] This enabled advances in mapping genes to specific chromosomes, which would eventually lead to the Human Genome Project.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In the 1960s, HeLa cells were sent on one of the early satellite missions to determine the long term effects of space travel on living cells and tissues.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Scientists discovered that HeLa cells divide more quickly in zero gravity.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The HeLa cell line was derived for use in cancer research.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] These cells proliferate abnormally rapidly, even compared with other cancer cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Like many other cancer cells, HeLa cells have an active version of telomerase during cell division, which copies telomeres over and over again.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] This prevents the incremental shortening of telomeres that is implicated in aging and eventual cell death.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In this way, the cells circumvent the Hayflick limit, which is the limited number of cell divisions that most normal cells can undergo before becoming senescent.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] This results in unlimited cell division and immortality.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Horizontal gene transfer from human papillomavirus 18 (HPV18) to human cervical cells created the HeLa genome, which is different from Henrietta Lacks's genome in various ways, including the number of chromosomes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Cancer cells are rapidly-dividing and tend to have many chromosome variations, and HeLa is no exception.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Roughly speaking, the HeLa karyotype contains 76–80 total chromosomes (making it "hypertriploid" since it's greater than the normal triploid number of 69), 22-25 of which are abnormal marker chromosomes (sometimes called "HeLa signature chromosomes").
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Despite this great difference from the normal human karyotype, the HeLa genome has largely retained this karyotype ever since it went into cell culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] This suggests that the aberrations may be representative of advanced cervical carcinomas and were probably present in the primary tumor.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] An 1999 study combined spectral karyotyping, FISH, and conventional cytogenic techniques to produce a "comprehensive and definitive" characterization of the karyotypes of six HeLa CCL-2 cells from two subclones.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Although most normal chromosomes are present in 2 copies, quite a few are present in 3 copies, and a few yet in 0 or 4 copies.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The numbers vary between cells and subclones, indicating that the karyotype is not completely stable.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The identities of all marker chromosomes were also elucidated down to the level of bands where possible.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] There is also variation in the presence and number of marker chromosomes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] As the "der" (derivative chromosome) notations indicate, most of the signature chromosomes are derived from multiple original chromosomes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HPV was found to have integrated onto 8q24 and two marker chromosomes containing this part of chromosome 8 (a der(5) and a der(22), underlined above).
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The genome sequencing project of 2013 (for HeLa CCL-2) allowed the analysis of chromosome abnormalities down to the level of singular nucleotides.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] It also managed to resolve two haplotypes of each chromosome, so now scientists know not only how many copies of a chromosome there is, but also how many copies from *each parent* there is; this also applies to parts of a chromosome.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] For example, it turns out that HPV18 only integrated into the version of chromosome 8 from one parent and that only two-thirds of the HPV-18 genome had been present.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Another genome sequencing project from 2013 dealt with the different HeLa Kyoto lineage.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] It did not resolve the haplotype but instead analyzed the transcriptome.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The complete genome and transcriptome of the Kyoto strain of HeLa cells were sequenced and published on 11 March 2013, without the Lacks family's knowledge.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Concerns were raised by the family, so the authors voluntarily withheld access to the sequence data.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Jay Shendure led a HeLa (CCL-2 strain) sequencing project at the University of Washington, which resulted in a paper that had been accepted for publication in March 2013 – but that was also put on hold while the Lacks family's privacy concerns were addressed.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] On 7 August 2013, NIH director Francis Collins announced a policy of controlled access to the cell line genome, based on an agreement reached after three meetings with the Lacks family.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The committee consists of six members, including representatives from the medical, scientific, and bioethics fields, as well as two members of the Lacks family.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] In an interview, Collins praised the Lacks family's willingness to participate in a situation that was thrust upon them.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] He described the whole experience with them as "powerful," saying that it brought together "science, scientific history and ethical concerns" in a unique way.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Shendure's haplotype-resolved genome and epigenome were published in August 2013.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Karyotypic, microarray, genomic, epigenomic, and transcriptomic data have allowed researchers to appreciate the scale and effect of the divergence among the many HeLa strains stored around the world's laboratories.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells are sometimes difficult to control, because they adapt to growth in tissue culture plates and invade and outcompete other cell lines.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Through improper maintenance, they have been known to contaminate other cell cultures in the same laboratory, interfering with biological research and forcing researchers to declare many results invalid.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The degree of HeLa cell contamination among other cell types is unknown, because few researchers test the identity or purity of already established cell lines.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] It has been shown that a substantial fraction of *in vitro* cell lines are contaminated with HeLa cells; estimates range from 10% to 20%.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] This observation suggests that any cell line may be susceptible to a degree of contamination.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Stanley Gartler (1967) and Walter Nelson-Rees (1975) were the first to publish on contamination of various cell lines by HeLa cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cell contamination has become a pervasive worldwide problem – affecting even the laboratories of many notable physicians, scientists, and researchers, including Jonas Salk.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The HeLa contamination problem also contributed to Cold War tensions.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The USSR and the USA had begun to cooperate in the war on cancer launched by President Richard Nixon, only to find that the exchanged cells were contaminated by HeLa.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Rather than focus on how to resolve the problem of HeLa cell contamination, many scientists and science writers continue to document this problem as simply a contamination issue – caused not by human error or shortcomings but by the hardiness, proliferation, or overpowering nature of HeLa cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Recent data suggest that cross-contamination is still a major problem with modern cell cultures.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The International Cell Line Authentication Committee (ICLAC) notes that many cases of cell line misidentification are the result of cross-contamination of the culture by another, faster-growing cell line.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] This calls into question the validity of the research done using contaminated cell lines, as certain attributes of the contaminant, which may come from an entirely different species or tissue, may be misattributed to the cell line under investigation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cell cultures can be contaminated by *Mycoplasma*.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Several species in this genus of bacteria can enter HeLa cells and adopt a parasitic lifestyle.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Infection does not cause obvious mass death, but causes gross alternations in experimental results.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] HeLa cells were described by evolutionary biologist Leigh Van Valen as an example of the contemporary creation of a new species, dubbed *Helacyton gartleri*, owing to their ability to replicate indefinitely and their non-human number of chromosomes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The species was named after geneticist Stanley M.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Gartler, whom Van Valen credits with discovering "the remarkable success of this species" (in the sense of having contaminated many other cell lines).
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Van Valen proposed the new family Helacytidae and the genus *Helacyton*, and in the same paper proposed a new species for HeLa cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] However, this proposal was not taken seriously by other prominent evolutionary biologists, nor by scientists in other disciplines.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Van Valen's argument that HeLa are a new species does not fulfill the criteria for an independent unicellular asexually reproducing species, because of the notorious instability of HeLa's karyotype and their lack of a strict ancestral-descendant lineage.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Duesberg *et al.* (2011) revisits the topic of cancer cell lines, speciation, and karyotypes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] They argue that the cell lines have a karyotype with a level of flexibility that is "within stable margins" as selection for the ability to replicate autonomously weeds out severe aneuploidies.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] Large rearrangements become rare after the cancer has become established while small copy number changes continue to provided variation in the population, with copy numbers typically oscillating ±1.
[src:cell-culture-methods/hela] The karyotypic difference between regular HeLa and a lineage selected for puromycin resistance is an example of ±1 variation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] An **immortalised cell line** is a population of cells from a multicellular organism that would normally not proliferate indefinitely but, due to mutation, have evaded normal cellular senescence and instead can keep undergoing division.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] The cells can therefore be grown for prolonged periods *in vitro*.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] The mutations required for immortality can occur naturally or be intentionally induced for experimental purposes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Immortal cell lines are a very important tool for research into the biochemistry and cell biology of multicellular organisms.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Immortalised cell lines have also found uses in biotechnology.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] An immortalised cell line should not be confused with stem cells, which can also divide indefinitely, but form a normal part of the development of a multicellular organism.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Some of them are normal cell lines (e.g. derived from stem cells).
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Other immortalised cell lines are the *in vitro* equivalent of cancerous cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Cancer occurs when a somatic cell that normally cannot divide undergoes mutations that cause deregulation of the normal cell cycle controls, leading to uncontrolled proliferation.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Immortalised cell lines have undergone similar mutations, allowing a cell type that would normally not be able to divide to be proliferated *in vitro*.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] The origins of some immortal cell lines – for example, HeLa human cells – are from naturally occurring cancers.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] HeLa, the first immortal human cell line on record to be successfully isolated and proliferated by a laboratory, was taken from Henrietta Lacks in 1951 at Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Immortalised cell lines are widely used as a simple model for more complex biological systems – for example, for the analysis of the biochemistry and cell biology of mammalian (including human) cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] The main advantage of using an immortal cell line for research is its immortality; the cells can be grown indefinitely in culture.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] This simplifies analysis of the biology of cells that may otherwise have a limited lifetime.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Immortalised cell lines can also be cloned, giving rise to a clonal population that can, in turn, be propagated indefinitely.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] This allows an analysis to be repeated many times on genetically identical cells, which is desirable for repeatable scientific experiments.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] The alternative, performing an analysis on primary cells from multiple tissue donors, does not have this advantage.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Immortalised cell lines find use in biotechnology, where they are a cost-effective way of growing cells similar to those found in a multicellular organism *in vitro*.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] The cells are used for a wide variety of purposes, from testing toxicity of compounds or drugs to production of eukaryotic proteins.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] While immortalised cell lines often originate from a well-known tissue type, they have undergone significant mutations to become immortal.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] This can alter the biology of the cell and must be taken into consideration in any analysis.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Further, cell lines can change genetically over multiple passages, leading to phenotypic differences among isolates and potentially different experimental results depending on when and with what strain isolate an experiment is conducted.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Many cell lines that are widely used for biomedical research have been contaminated and overgrown by other, more aggressive cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] For example, supposed thyroid lines were actually melanoma cells, supposed prostate tissue was actually bladder cancer, and supposed normal uterine cultures were actually breast cancer.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Introduction of a viral gene that partially deregulates the cell cycle (e.g., the adenovirus type 5 E1 gene was used to immortalise the HEK 293 cell line; the Epstein–Barr virus can immortalise B lymphocytes by infection).
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Artificial expression of key proteins required for immortality, for example telomerase which prevents degradation of chromosome ends during DNA replication in eukaryotes.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Hybridoma technology, specifically used for generating immortalised antibody-producing B cell lines, where an antibody-producing B cell is fused with a myeloma (B cell cancer) cell.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] There are several examples of immortalised cell lines, each with different properties.
[src:cell-culture-methods/immortalised-cell-line] Most immortalised cell lines are classified by the cell type they originated from or are most similar to biologically.
[src:cell-culture-methods/trypsinization] For experimental purposes, cells are often cultivated in containers that take the form of plastic flasks or plates.
[src:cell-culture-methods/trypsinization] In such flasks, cells are provided with a growth medium comprising the essential nutrients required for proliferation, and the cells adhere to the container and each other as they grow.
[src:cell-culture-methods/trypsinization] This process of cell culture or tissue culture requires a method to dissociate the cells from the container and each other.
[src:cell-culture-methods/trypsinization] Trypsin, an enzyme commonly found in the digestive tract, can be used to "digest" the proteins that facilitate adhesion to the container and between cells.
[src:cell-culture-methods/trypsinization] Once cells have detached from their container it is necessary to deactivate the trypsin, unless the trypsin is synthetic, as cell surface proteins will also be cleaved over time and this will affect cell functioning.
[src:cell-culture-methods/trypsinization] Serum can be used to inactivate trypsin, as it contains protease inhibitors.
[src:cell-culture-methods/trypsinization] Because of the presence of these inhibitors, the serum must be removed before treatment of a growth vessel with trypsin and must not be added again to the growth vessel until cells have detached from their growth surface - this detachment can be confirmed by visual observation using a microscope.
[src:cell-culture-methods/trypsinization] Trypsinization is often used to permit passage of adherent cells to a new container, observation for experimentation, or reduction of the degree of confluency in a culture flask through the removal of a percentage of the cells.
